org.settings4j
Interface Connector

All Known Implementing Classes:
AbstractConnector, AbstractDBConnector, AbstractPropertyConnector, CachedConnectorWrapper, ClasspathConnector, FilteredConnectorWrapper, FSConnector, HibernateDBConnector, JNDIConnector, PreferencesConnector, PropertyFileConnector, SystemPropertyConnector
public interface Connector

An implementation of this Interface can return Values for a given key.
Not every implementation can write a value for a given key (e.g.: ClasspathConnector )
String, byte[] (content) and Objects should be possible.

A Connector can use the Helper Implementations ContentResolver and ObjectResolver for internal use.
Not ervery Connector needs them, Read the Javadoc of the concrete implementaiton.

 
 Example configuration in settings4j.xml:
 --------------------------------------
 <connector name="ClasspathConnector" class="org.settings4j.connector.ClasspathConnector" >
     <objectResolver-ref ref="DefaultObjectResolver" />
 </connector>
 --------------------------------------

Author:
Harald.Brabenetz

addConnector

void addConnector(Connector connector)
Add a Connector if you needed inside the init() Methode.
Or you can use this connectors inside the settings4j.xml to set a parameter/property 
 
 Example configuration in settings4j.xml:
 --------------------------------------
 <connector name="PropertyFileConnector" class="org.settings4j.connector.PropertyFileConnector">
     <param name="propertyFromContent"
          value="${connectors.content['org/settings4j/config/propertyFile.properties']}" />
     <contentResolver-ref ref="DefaultContentResolver" />
     <connector-ref ref="ClasspathConnector" />
 </connector>
 --------------------------------------

Parameters:
connector - the Connector to set.

init

void init()
Will be called after all properties have been set. This function will only called one times.
